          <p class="ab-player-bio">A former U.S. National Team athlete who competed at the highest levels of American badminton before transitioning into coaching — where his experience now directly benefits the next generation of American players.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <h3 style="margin-top:48px;">The Rise of Badminton in America</h3>
      <p>
        Over the past decade, participation in badminton across the United States has grown significantly. College clubs at institutions like MIT, Harvard, Stanford, and UC Berkeley have become feeder pipelines for national competition. Youth programs are expanding in cities from Los Angeles to New York to Chicago to Boston — and Massachusetts, in particular, has emerged as one of the more active and organized state-level badminton communities in the country.
      </p>
      <p>
        USA Badminton continues to invest in elite development pathways, coaching certification programs, and international tournament exposure for American players. The ambition is clear: to compete not just at the Pan American level, but to challenge the best in the world on the BWF World Tour and at the Olympic Games.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── PAN AM ── -->
  <section id="panam" class="ab-section ab-panam">
    <div class="ab-section-inner">
      <p class="ab-section-label">Americas &amp; Beyond</p>
      <h2>Pan America, the BWF Circuit, and America's Role in the Global Game</h2>
      <div class="ab-divider ab-divider-inv"></div>
      <div class="ab-badge-row">
        <span class="ab-badge">🌎 Pan American Championships</span>
        <span class="ab-badge">🎖️ Pan American Games</span>
        <span class="ab-badge">🏆 BWF World Tour</span>
        <span class="ab-badge">🌍 Thomas &amp; Uber Cup</span>
        <span class="ab-badge">⚡ Sudirman Cup</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Within the Americas, the Badminton Pan Am Confederation (BPC) governs the sport across 45 member associations. The Pan American Badminton Championships are held annually, serving as both a qualifying pathway toward World Championships and Olympic selection, and as the premier individual title for the continent.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Pan American Games — held every four years in the year preceding the Summer Olympics — provide one of badminton's most competitive and emotionally charged continental stages. The USA has fielded teams in badminton at the Pan American Games repeatedly, and its athletes compete with the ambition of earning automatic qualification berths for the Olympic Games.
      </p>
      <h3>Why Continental Competitions Matter</h3>
      <p>
        For a sport that has historically been dominated by Asian nations, Pan American events represent something important: a proving ground where American athletes can test themselves against fierce continental rivals — Brazil, Canada, Peru, and Guatemala, among others — and build the world ranking points needed to qualify for the Olympic Games. Every point earned in Lima, Cali, or Guadalajara is a step toward Paris, Los Angeles, or Brisbane.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Massachusetts Badminton Foundation is proud to have supported Massachusetts State Team athletes nominated for these very tournaments — including the Junior National Championship and the Pan America Championship — through its scholarship program. When a Massachusetts player steps onto a court at an international competition, the MBF community is behind them.
      </p>
      <h3>Badminton at a Glance: Why the World Can't Stop Watching</h3>
      <p>
        To understand why badminton commands massive television audiences in Asia — and growing ones everywhere else — you need to watch just one high-level rally. The combination of blistering speed, deft deception, and the almost acrobatic athleticism required to retrieve a shuttlecock from a seemingly impossible position produces a level of spectacle that is genuinely hard to match. Major finals at the All England Open, the Indonesia Open, or the Olympic Games draw hundreds of millions of viewers globally. The sport's global governing body, the BWF, counts over 220 member nations — more than FIFA — making it one of the broadest participation sports on Earth.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

